00:01:37.900 --> 00:01:40.790
We've got a big Cloud
event that's running there.

00:01:40.790 --> 00:01:43.930
And Urs, who heads up
our infrastructure, that

00:01:43.930 --> 00:01:47.420
runs all of our
Google services, is

00:01:47.420 --> 00:01:49.640
making a big
announcement about Cloud.

00:01:49.640 --> 00:01:52.130
And he's making an
announcement on a number

00:01:52.130 --> 00:01:53.280
of different points.

00:01:53.280 --> 00:01:56.742
So I haven't been able to
share slides with you on this,

00:01:56.742 --> 00:01:58.700
but I wanted to give you
some of the headlines,

00:01:58.700 --> 00:02:00.650
so you can go away,
think about that.

00:02:00.650 --> 00:02:03.200
And take that with you.

00:02:03.200 --> 00:02:06.530
And the first big
change is around price.

00:02:06.530 --> 00:02:10.009
So in Google, we're a little
bit concerned in the sense

00:02:10.009 --> 00:02:11.240
that you've got Moore's Law.

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:15.860
And that's creating an
erosion of price on hardware,

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:17.790
but you're not necessarily
getting those price

00:02:17.790 --> 00:02:20.090
reductions-- in the
erosion of price

00:02:20.090 --> 00:02:23.770
on hardware-- that gets
translated to you as a Cloud

00:02:23.770 --> 00:02:25.000
customer.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.770
So the first big thing that
we're actually offering

00:02:28.770 --> 00:02:34.410
is a 32% price drop in Compute
Engine, a 30% drop for App

00:02:34.410 --> 00:02:38.040
Engine, a 68% drop
for Cloud Storage,

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:41.740
which is pretty massive,
and a huge 85% percent cut

00:02:41.740 --> 00:02:45.060
for Big Query-- which
we believe is about 75%

00:02:45.060 --> 00:02:47.170
cheaper than any
other alternative.

00:02:47.170 --> 00:02:50.920
So we are expecting this to
have a significant impact

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:53.720
on the Cloud landscape as well.

00:02:53.720 --> 00:02:59.220
So all of you will have
with you some App Credits

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:01.220
as well-- some Cloud
Credits-- that you

00:03:01.220 --> 00:03:02.970
go in those little note pads.

00:03:02.970 --> 00:03:05.180
So use those.

00:03:05.180 --> 00:03:07.740
Explore the Cloud platform,
and get to know it better,

00:03:07.740 --> 00:03:11.630
because it's incredibly
cost competitive right now.

00:03:11.630 --> 00:03:15.540
The second big announcement
that Urs will be talking about,

00:03:15.540 --> 00:03:17.660
or is talking about,
is about simplicity.

00:03:22.410 --> 00:03:26.240
To understand the pricing models
of Cloud worlds is complex.

00:03:26.240 --> 00:03:28.820
So figuring out things
like reserved instances,

00:03:28.820 --> 00:03:32.710
and exactly how much you're
going to pay is a tricky art.

00:03:32.710 --> 00:03:35.630
So what we're actually
implementing now

00:03:35.630 --> 00:03:39.340
is something called automatic
discounts for steady state

00:03:39.340 --> 00:03:40.230
workloads.

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:42.016
So that makes it a
lot simpler for you.

00:03:42.016 --> 00:03:44.540
We check your usage
over a monthly period,

00:03:44.540 --> 00:03:47.422
and then apply the price drops
right at the end of the month,

00:03:47.422 --> 00:03:49.630
and so you actually make
some massive savings on that

00:03:49.630 --> 00:03:50.420
as well.

00:03:50.420 --> 00:03:55.030
So in effect, you can save up
to about 53% for Compute Engine,

00:03:55.030 --> 00:03:57.890
instance is if you've
got 24 by 7 usage.

00:03:57.890 --> 00:04:01.660
So again, big cost
savings there.

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:04.540
He's announcing about new
operating system support.

00:04:04.540 --> 00:04:08.940
So we'll have Susie and Red Hat
support, Windows Server 2008

00:04:08.940 --> 00:04:12.040
R2, and we're also
supporting Cloud DNS.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:16.180
And so you can have DNS
as a service as well.

00:04:16.180 --> 00:04:19.360
And finally, we're
also building more

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:21.700
on what Mandy was talking
about earlier, blurring

00:04:21.700 --> 00:04:23.590
this distinction
between infrastructure

00:04:23.590 --> 00:04:26.130
as a service and
platform as a service.

00:04:26.130 --> 00:04:28.700
So making this much
more of a continuum.

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:31.210
So in the past,
you typically have

00:04:31.210 --> 00:04:32.620
some sort of sense
of compromise.

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:36.280
If you wanted the auto-scaling
functionality of App Engine,

00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:38.647
but maybe a language
wasn't supported on it,

00:04:38.647 --> 00:04:40.480
you might have to go
towards Compute Engine,

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:42.600
but you wouldn't have
the auto-scale with it.

00:04:42.600 --> 00:04:46.000
But now with this hybrid model,
with managed VMs, which is now

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.430
in production, you can go beyond
that traditional compromise.

00:04:49.430 --> 00:04:52.800
You run whatever you want,
auto-scale it as well,

00:04:52.800 --> 00:04:56.850
on App Engine with
this managed VM model.

00:04:56.850 --> 00:04:59.850
And so summarizing all of that,
because that's quite a lot

00:04:59.850 --> 00:05:01.892
to take on board there.

00:05:01.892 --> 00:05:04.100
I guess you can take away
that we're pretty committed

00:05:04.100 --> 00:05:07.220
to Cloud, and that's
pretty important to us.

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:09.820
Second, we're committed
to simplicity.

00:05:09.820 --> 00:05:12.760
We want to make it easier to
understand the Cloud, easier

00:05:12.760 --> 00:05:14.650
to be billed about
that, and easier

00:05:14.650 --> 00:05:16.200
to be able to predict things.

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:18.390
And third, we are
rethinking the way

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:21.300
Cloud computing can be done
with this hybrid model.

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:23.100
So ultimately, all of
this should save you

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:25.280
time and money and effort.

00:05:25.280 --> 00:05:30.080
So lots to talk about there,
and lots to take in there.

00:05:30.080 --> 00:05:31.770
But the other thing
to mention, as well,

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:35.360
